® 4.0 software (Biopac Systems Inc., Goleta, CA, USA) on a laptop (Dell Precision Workstation, Dell Inc., Round Rock, USA) for post-flight analyses. A solid-state hard drive was used for data storage to prevent automatic computer shutdown at 0 Gz, which would be triggered by the laptop built-in free-fall sensor that would mistakenly indicate that the computer was falling down during the 0 Gz phases. Rebreathing maneuvers were subsequently identified from the thoracic impedance signal. The finger blood pressure and heart rate were averaged across the three relevant breaths required for the measurement of the SIrb, and these averages were then processed as single blood pressure and heart rate data points for further analysis (Limper et al. 2011).
